		<item>
			<title>Interview with Associate Justice Goodwin H. Liu of The Supreme Court of California, US</title>
			<description>&lt;p style="text-align: center; "&gt;   &lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/thumb/180/209329.jpg" alt="1111.jpg" style="text-align: start;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;   &lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="margin-bottom: 15px; padding: 15px; background-color: #eeeeee;"&gt;   &lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;In January 2025, The Korea Legislation Research Institute (“&lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;KLRI&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;”) established The Center for the Legal Foundations, Education and Research (“&lt;/span&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;CLFER&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;”) to restore and reconceptualize the foundations of legal education. On the occasion of the inauguration of The CLFER, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;The Law Times&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt; had an interview with Honorable Associate Justice Goodwin H. Liu of the Supreme Court of California, US, who visited Korea at KLRI’s invitation. The CLFER aims to strengthen foundational legal theory and research and to serve as a leading hub for interdisciplinary studies. Associate Justice Liu’s visit was part of this initiative. The full interview is as below.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;   &lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;1. California is known for its diverse population encompassing a wide range of racial and cultural backgrounds. Have you ever felt that this diversity influences judicial decisions or deliberations in the judiciary?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;We are fortunate to have outstanding individuals from all backgrounds and walks of life serving as judges in California’s courts.Judges are public servants and members of their communities, and they bring their experiences and humanity to the task of applying law to facts with awareness of social context and the interests of justice.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;2. I have read your recent article, The Bamboo Ceiling in Law, and found it particularly thought-provoking. As I understand it, the paper reflects on the institutional and cultural barriers that Asian American legal professionals would and do face. Could you elaborate on the key messages you intended to deliver through this research and how it has contributed to discourse within and outside the legal profession?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;   &lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;Over the past 50 years, Asian Americans have been the fast-growing racial group in the legal profession.They have penetrated every sector of the legal profession in substantial numbers.But few Asian Americans reach the top ranks of the legal profession, especially equity partnership in large law firms.Obstacles to advancement include lack of mentorship and leadership training, as well as stereotypes that portray Asian Americans as “good workers” but not “leadership material.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;3. Korea’s law school system was introduced to cultivate legal professionals with diverse life experiences. However, some argue that the system has not fully realized this vision. In the US, how has the legal profession succeeded in integrating individuals with varied and different backgrounds, and what institutional support has made this possible?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;Over the past decades, U.S. law schools have made substantial efforts to including students from groups historically excluded or underrepresented in the law.Those efforts have resulted in greater racial and ethnic diversity in the legal profession, but there is still much work to do to ensure that all groups feel included in law schools and the legal profession.This includes making sure that all students feel welcome in speaking freely and expressing their views, without fear of being canceled or ostracized.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;   &lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/thumb/180/209329.jpg" alt="22222.jpg" style="text-align: start;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;4. The US federal judiciary has a “Senior Judge” system. Is there a comparable arrangement in California? If so, could you briefly describe its function and how it contributes to the judiciary and the public?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;California has an “Assigned Judges” program that allows the Chief Justice to appoint retired judges to temporarily fill vacancies or help reduce calendar congestion in the courts.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;5. There is a saying that “law breathes with the times.” How are changes in society reflected in judicial decisions? Of such changes, are there core values you consider essential to maintaining public trust and confidence in the judiciary and its decisions?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;The U.S. Constitution was written to endure for the ages; the Framers established a number of general principles and did not claim to know how those principles would be applied in every future circumstance.In keeping with the Framers’ vision, the judiciary interprets many constitutional principles with awareness of societal conditions and the needs and challenges facing the nation.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;6. In Korea, there has been a growing trend of various social conflicts being brought before the courts, often accompanied by concerns over what is called the “politicization of the judiciary.” As a jurist, how do you view such a phenomenon? Judicial decisions in Korea are sometimes or often read in a political context, which raises concerns about the independence of the judiciary. How about California or the US? Are there similar concerns or discussions in the US? Could you share your views on this if you have any?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;Courts everywhere are being drawn into legal cases that are also political disputes.When it is necessary to decide such cases, courts must scrupulously follow the law and, whenever possible, strive to achieve unanimity or a broad consensus that will garner public acceptance of judicial decisions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;7. The US is known for its well-established jury system. During your tenure on the bench of the Supreme Court of California, have you come across instances where jury verdicts and judicial opinions diverged? If so, how have you reconciled such situations?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;Only in rare instances may judges override a jury verdict; in those instances, it must be clear that the jury’s verdict is unsupported by the evidence or contrary to the law.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;8. In every civil judgment, there are winners and losers. It is of utmost importance for trust and confidence in the judiciary and judicial system that parties accept judicial outcomes. What are your hopes regarding how parties perceive and respond to the courts and their decisions?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;In every decision, the courts must strive to ensure that all parties, win or lose, feel that they have been respected and that their arguments have been heard and fairly considered.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;9. There is a growing global interest in leveraging artificial intelligence (“AI”) as a tool to support judicial processes. Has the Supreme Court of California explored or implemented any initiatives to improve access to justice through technology?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Arial;"&gt;AI is a topic of active discussion throughout the legal profession, but the California Supreme Court has not yet adopted any policies on the use of AI.More generally, I believe it is useful to explore how technology, including remote appearances, can make it easier for ordinary people to access the justice system.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</description>
